"Shindell D., Lamarque J.-F., Unger N., Koch D., Faluvegi G., Bauer S., Ammann M., Cofala J., Teich H.","Climate forcing and air quality change due to regional emissions reductions by economic sector",2008,"Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics","8","23",,"7101","7113",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-57549096927&partnerID=40&md5=3747eb5863962399d09d65d347e60bed","NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; National Center for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO, United States; International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis, Laxenburg, Austria","Shindell, D., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Lamarque, J.-F., National Center for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, CO, United States; Unger, N., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Koch, D., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Faluvegi, G., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Bauer, S., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Ammann, M., International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis, Laxenburg, Austria; Cofala, J., International Institute for Applied Systems Analysis, Laxenburg, Austria; Teich, H., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States","We examine the air quality (AQ) and radiative forcing (RF) response to emissions reductions by economic sector for North America and developing Asia in the CAM and GISS composition/climate models. Decreases in annual average surface particulate are relatively robust, with intermodel variations in magnitude typically <30% and very similar spatial structure. Surface ozone responses are small and highly model dependent. The largest net RF results from reductions in emissions from the North America industrial/power and developing Asia domestic fuel burning sectors. Sulfate reductions dominate the first case, for which intermodel variations in the sulfate (or total) aerosol optical depth (AOD) responses are ∼30% and the modeled spatial patterns of the AOD reductions are highly correlated (R=0.9). Decreases in BC dominate the developing Asia domestic fuel burning case, and show substantially greater model-to-model differences. Intermodel variations in tropospheric ozone burden changes are also large, though aerosol changes dominate those cases with substantial net climate forcing. The results indicate that across-the-board emissions reductions in domestic fuel burning in developing Asia and in surface transportation in North America are likely to offer the greatest potential for substantial, simultaneous improvement in local air quality and near-term mitigation of global climate change via short-lived species. Conversely, reductions in industrial/power emissions have the potential to accelerate near-term warming, though they would improve AQ and have a long-term cooling effect on climate. These broad conclusions appear robust to intermodel differences.",,"aerosol property; air quality; climate change; climate forcing; climate modeling; developing world; emission control; industrial emission; Asia; Eurasia; North America",,,,,,"Andreae, M.O., Merlet, P., Emission of trace gases and aerosols from, biomass burning (2001) Global Biogeochem. Cy, 15, pp. 955-966; Arellano, A.F.J., Kasibhatla, P.S., Giglio, L., van der Werf, G.R., Randerson, J.T., Top-down estimates of global CO sources using mopitt measurements (2004) Geophys. Res. Lett, 31, pp. L01104. , doi:10.1029/2003GL018609; Bauer, S.E., Mishchenko, M.I., Lacis, A., Zhang, S., Perlwitz, J., Metzger, S.M., Do sulfate and nitrate coatings on mineral dust have important effects on radiative properties and climate modeling? (2006) J. Geophys. Res, 112, pp. D06307. , doi:10.1029/2005JD006977; Bauer, S.E., Koch, D., Unger, N., Metzger, S.M., Shindell, D.T., Streets, D., Nitrate aerosols today and in 2030: Importance relative to other aerosol species and tro